<subSubSection id="C3520E80FD45D8723FAF21E7782140E6" pageId="1" pageNumber="78" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BF75D0BFD45D8723FAF21E7782140E6" blockId="1.[151,760,1348,2076]" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis id="B93C8119FD45D8723FAF21E778EB43E6" bold="true" box="[151,423,1413,1436]" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">Comparative diagnosis.</emphasis>
Males of 
<taxonomicName id="4C482688FD45D8723D2421E67BFF43E6" authorityName="Wittmer" authorityYear="1966" box="[540,691,1412,1436]" class="Insecta" family="Cantharidae" genus="Pygodiscodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93C8119FD45D8723D2421E67BFF43E6" box="[540,691,1412,1436]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">Pygodiscodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differ from 
<emphasis id="B93C8119FD45D8723FEC21C6787643C6" box="[212,314,1444,1468]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">Discodon</emphasis>
in the outer claws on the mid- and hind tarsi with a small, fine tooth protruding in an acute angle (in 
<emphasis id="B93C8119FD45D8723F81218678524386" box="[185,286,1508,1532]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">Discodon</emphasis>
, the outer claw is apparently split at the apex), and in the last tergite variously shaped, with impressions, constrictions and prominences, and a pair of juxtaposed glandular pores at the apex (in 
<emphasis id="B93C8119FD45D8723ED122267B034026" box="[489,591,1604,1628]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">Discodon</emphasis>
, the last tergite is usually broad and flat with single posterior glandular pore on either side).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3520E80FD45D8723FAF22C77DF742EF" pageId="1" pageNumber="78" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BF75D0BFD45D8723FAF22C77C6945CF" blockId="1.[151,760,1348,2076]" lastBlockId="1.[828,1437,190,1525]" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis id="B93C8119FD45D8723FAF22C7786E40C6" bold="true" box="[151,290,1701,1724]" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">Description.</emphasis>
Body length: 5.0–8.8 mm. Head dark brown to black, sometimes light brown behind eyes; frons, clypeus and base of mandibles pale yellow to orange; apex of mandibles and palpi light to dark brown; antennae dark brown to black, sometimes antennomeres yellowish-white; pronotum pale yellow to orange with dark brown to black medial patch; legs light brown to black; thorax, elytra and abdomen dark brown to black. Head, antennae, pronotum, and elytra densely covered with short and thin pubescence. 
<emphasis id="B93C8119FD45D8723F8D23A679B041A6" box="[181,252,1988,2012]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">Males</emphasis>
: Head, including eyes, nearly as wide as pronotum; frons flat; occipital region convex; clypeus emarginated, slightly prominent medially; mandibles falciform, acute, without accessory teeth. Last maxillary and labial palpomeres securiform. Antennae (
<figureCitation id="1373418EFD45D8723A1F24BC7CD8468F" box="[1319,1428,222,245]" captionStart="Figs 7–12" captionStartId="3.[151,188,1973,1992]" captionTargetBox="[151,759,814,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[136,763,792,1956]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 7–12. Antennae of Pygodiscodon species (dorsal view). 7 – Pygodiscodon apicicornis (Pic, 1910); 8 – P. gurupi sp. nov.; 9 – P. monoceros sp. nov.; 10 – P. obscurus Wittmer, 1966; 11 – P. similis sp. nov.; 12 – P. touroulti Constantin, 2010. Scale bars = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3676786" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3676786/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">Figs 7–12</figureCitation>
) long, surpassing middle of elytra; antennomeres conical to subserrate, slightly compressed dorso-ventrally, with longitudinal lines. Eyes small and slightly prominent to large and very prominent. Pronotum wider than long; anterior margin slightly to broadly arched; lateral margins slightly emarginated, distinctly notched in basal third. Elytra almost parallel, wider medially, around twice longer than wide. Wings (
<figureCitation id="1373418EFD45D8723CEC25BC7D6F478F" box="[980,1059,478,501]" captionStart="Figs 13–16" captionStartId="4.[151,188,976,995]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,191,967]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,190,967]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 13–16. Legs and wing of Pygodiscodon species. 13 – Metathoracic coxae, P. gurupi sp. nov. 14–16 – P. obscurus Wittmer, 1966: 14 – Left wing (dorsal view); 15 – Prothoracic tarsal claws; 16 – Mesothoracic tarsal claws. Scale bars: 13 = 0.5 mm; 14 = 1.0 mm; 15–16 = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3676788" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3676788/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
) ‘Silis type’: radial cell 2R1 open, vein 
<taxonomicName id="4C482688FD45D8723C4B259C7AB3446F" box="[883,1023,510,533]" pageId="1" pageNumber="78" rank="subSpecies" subSpecies="incomplete">r incomplete</taxonomicName>
, r-m not coinciding with r, Cu and A not divided, cu-a barely visible. Legs slender; tarsomeres increasing in length from pro- to hind leg; forth tarsomeres with basal transverse split; inner prothoracic tarsal claws (
<figureCitation id="1373418EFD45D8723C7C261C7ADC44EF" box="[836,912,638,661]" captionStart="Figs 13–16" captionStartId="4.[151,188,976,995]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,191,967]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,190,967]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 13–16. Legs and wing of Pygodiscodon species. 13 – Metathoracic coxae, P. gurupi sp. nov. 14–16 – P. obscurus Wittmer, 1966: 14 – Left wing (dorsal view); 15 – Prothoracic tarsal claws; 16 – Mesothoracic tarsal claws. Scale bars: 13 = 0.5 mm; 14 = 1.0 mm; 15–16 = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3676788" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3676788/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
) broadly lobed basally; outer claws on meso- and metathoracic tarsal claws (
<figureCitation id="1373418EFD45D8723B6226FC7DEB44CF" box="[1114,1191,670,693]" captionStart="Figs 13–16" captionStartId="4.[151,188,976,995]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,191,967]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,190,967]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 13–16. Legs and wing of Pygodiscodon species. 13 – Metathoracic coxae, P. gurupi sp. nov. 14–16 – P. obscurus Wittmer, 1966: 14 – Left wing (dorsal view); 15 – Prothoracic tarsal claws; 16 – Mesothoracic tarsal claws. Scale bars: 13 = 0.5 mm; 14 = 1.0 mm; 15–16 = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3676788" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3676788/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
) with small, fine tooth protruding in acute angle. Abdomen (
<figureCitation id="1373418EFD45D8723BFE26DC7C7344AF" box="[1222,1343,702,725]" captionStart-0="Figs 17–25" captionStart-1="Figs 26–34" captionStartId-0="5.[151,188,1999,2018]" captionStartId-1="6.[151,188,1998,2017]" captionTargetBox-0="[151,1435,241,1899]" captionTargetBox-1="[152,1435,190,1899]" captionTargetId-0="figure@5.[151,1436,189,1899]" captionTargetId-1="figure@6.[151,1436,189,1899]" captionTargetPageId-0="5" captionTargetPageId-1="6" captionText-0="Figs 17–25.Abdominal apex of Pygodiscodon species (ventral, dorsal and lateral views). 17–19 – P. apicicorne (Pic, 1910); 20–22 – P. gurupi sp. nov.; 23–25 – P. monoceros sp. nov. Scale bar = 1.0 mm." captionText-1="Figs 26–34.Abdominal apex of Pygodiscodon species (ventral, dorsal and lateral views). 26–28 – P. obscurus Wittmer, 1966; 29–31 – P. similis sp. nov.; 32–34 – P. touroulti Constantin, 2010. Scale bar = 1.0 mm." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3676790" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3676793" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/3676790/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/3676793/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">Figs 17–34</figureCitation>
) slightly sclerotized; last ventrite bilobed; last tergite variously shaped, with impressions, constrictions and prominences; pair of juxtaposed apical glandular pores. Aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="1373418EFD45D8723A55277C7ACF452F" captionStart-0="Figs 41–49" captionStart-1="Figs 50–58" captionStartId-0="9.[151,188,1956,1975]" captionStartId-1="10.[151,188,1956,1975]" captionTargetBox-0="[151,1436,189,1831]" captionTargetBox-1="[151,1436,189,1844]" captionTargetId-0="figure@9.[151,1436,189,1831]" captionTargetId-1="figure@10.[151,1436,189,1844]" captionTargetPageId-0="9" captionTargetPageId-1="10" captionText-0="Figs 41–49. Aedeagi of Pygodiscodon species (ventral, lateral and dorsal views). 41–43 – Pygodiscodon apicicornis (Pic, 1910); 44–46 – P. gurupi sp. nov.; 47–49 – P. monoceros sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.2 mm." captionText-1="Figs 50–58.Aedeagi of Pygodiscodon species (ventral, lateral and dorsal views). 50–52 – P. obscurus Wittmer, 1966; 53–55 – P. similis sp. nov.; 56–58 – P. touroulti Constantin, 2010. Scale bar = 0.2 mm." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3676799" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3676801" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/3676799/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/3676801/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">Figs 41–58</figureCitation>
): tegmen very short dorsally and long and broad ventrally, completely covering median lobe; parameres slender; median lobe broad and membranous; internal sac partially exposed, bearing spine-like sclerites.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF75D0BFD45D8723C6227DF7DF742EF" blockId="1.[828,1437,190,1525]" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis id="B93C8119FD45D8723C6227DF7AFF45AF" box="[858,947,957,981]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">Females</emphasis>
: similar to males; eyes slightly smaller and less prominent; antennae shorter, without longitudinal lines; pronotum without lateral notches; tarsal claws simple; abdominal ventrite VII (
<figureCitation id="1373418EFD45D8723B71207C7D8B424F" box="[1097,1223,1054,1077]" captionStart="Figs 35–40" captionStartId="7.[151,188,469,488]" captionTargetBox="[152,743,190,446]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,748,189,447]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 35–40.Abdominal ventrite VII of females of Pygodiscodon species, ventral view. 35 – Pygodiscodon apicicornis (Pic, 1910); 36 – P. gurupi sp. nov.; 37 – P. monoceros sp. nov.; 38 – P.obscurus Wittmer, 1966; 39 – P. similis sp. nov.; 40 – P. touroulti Constantin, 2010. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3676795" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3676795/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">Figs 35–40</figureCitation>
) entire, wider than long, lateral margins arched, distal margin with projecting tip; abdominal tergite VIII simple, without distinct impressions, constrictions or prominences.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3520E80FD45D8723C0420FC7DF543CF" pageId="1" pageNumber="78" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BF75D0BFD45D8723C0420FC7DF543CF" blockId="1.[828,1437,190,1525]" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis id="B93C8119FD45D8723C0420FC7A8E42CF" bold="true" box="[828,962,1182,1205]" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">Etymology.</emphasis>
No etymology was given in the original description of 
<taxonomicName id="4C482688FD45D8723CE220DF7D3D42AF" authorityName="Wittmer" authorityYear="1966" box="[986,1137,1213,1237]" class="Insecta" family="Cantharidae" genus="Pygodiscodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93C8119FD45D8723CE220DF7D3D42AF" box="[986,1137,1213,1237]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">Pygodiscodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The name is derived from 
<emphasis id="B93C8119FD45D8723C0420BF7AEE428F" box="[828,930,1245,1269]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">Discodon</emphasis>
Gorham, 1881, established by this author on the notching in the sides of pronotum of males (
<emphasis id="B93C8119FD45D8723A27209F7C1B436F" box="[1311,1367,1277,1301]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">disco</emphasis>
refers to the centre of pronotum and - 
<emphasis id="B93C8119FD45D8723BA5217F7D9F434F" box="[1181,1235,1309,1333]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">odon</emphasis>
(m.) is the Greek word for tooth). Therefore, the name 
<taxonomicName id="4C482688FD45D8723BEE215F7C21432F" authorityName="Wittmer" authorityYear="1966" box="[1238,1389,1341,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Cantharidae" genus="Pygodiscodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93C8119FD45D8723BEE215F7C21432F" box="[1238,1389,1341,1365]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="78">Pygodiscodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a masculine (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD920FAFD45D8723C80213C7D76430F" author="ICZN" box="[952,1082,1374,1397]" pageId="1" pageNumber="78" refId="ref11014" refString="ICZN 1999: International code of zoological nomenclature. Fourth edition. The International Trust for Zoological Nomenclature, London, xxix + 306 pp." type="book" year="1999">ICZN 1999</bibRefCitation>
, art. 30.1.2), and the mandatory changes in spellings of species names are henceforth made accordingly (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD920FAFD45D8723CFF21FC7D0A43CF" author="ICZN" box="[967,1094,1438,1461]" pageId="1" pageNumber="78" refId="ref11014" refString="ICZN 1999: International code of zoological nomenclature. Fourth edition. The International Trust for Zoological Nomenclature, London, xxix + 306 pp." type="book" year="1999">ICZN 1999</bibRefCitation>
, art. 34.2).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
